      "side": 1,
      "message": "I think this claim oversells what the two-file split actually achieves, and the framing is worth tightening.\n\nThe defining property of go.work is not that it is a second file, but that it lives *outside* the module and is gitignored by default, so machine-specific directory replaces physically cannot be committed alongside the module. This proposal instead puts directory replaces in cue.mod/local-module.cue, which is committed by default (see \"Why not `.gitignore` `local-module.cue` by default?\"), mitigated only by an opt-in \"tooling can warn\" check.\n\nSo the accidental-commit-of-directory-replaces problem that go.work was designed to eliminate is relocated into a new committed file, not eliminated. The design makes such commits easier to *detect* (a dedicated file, a warning), which is a real benefit — but that is a different and weaker claim than \"avoiding the problems that Go encountered.\"\n\nTwo concrete suggestions:\n- Soften the abstract/background to the honest claim, e.g. \"making development-time configuration explicit and easy to detect before publication\" rather than \"avoiding the problems that Go encountered.\"\n- Either way, the document should confront the residual footgun head-on: a directory replace like `replace: \"../local-foo\"` is inherently non-portable, yet nothing structurally stops it being committed. Is the warning enough? Should directory replaces (as opposed to module-version replaces) be gitignored or rejected at commit/publish time, while module-version replaces stay committable? The \"Why not `.gitignore` by default?\" section gestures at this distinction but stops short of a mechanism.",
      "revId": "3246977dd4008d03b285a57cd301568ca766dcb3",
      "serverId": "d5d70762-12d0-45a1-890d-524b12d3f735"
    },
